<article>
    <h1>An&#xAD;other Su&#xAD;perb ride</h1>
    <h2>Skoda&#x2019;s Su&#xAD;perb saloon is now pow&#xAD;ered by a more ef&#xAD;fi&#xAD;cient and cleaner 2-litre engine</h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200822/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-08-22"><time>2020-08-22</time></a>
        - <span>MOTORING</span>
        - <span role="byline">Christo&#xAD;pher Tan Se&#xAD;nior Cor&#xAD;re&#xAD;spon&#xAD;dent chris&#xAD;tan@sph.com.sg&#xD;&#xA;&#x2022; Fol&#xAD;low Christo&#xAD;pher Tan on In&#xAD;sta&#xAD;gram @chris.mo&#xAD;tor&#xAD;ing</span>
    </section>

    <p>When the cur­rent-gen­er­a­tion Skoda Su­perb l anded here two years ago, it had a 220hp 2-litre engine. Last year, a 180hp 1.8-litre vari­ant was launched to re­place it.</p>
    <p>Now, the Su­perb is back to a 2-litre engine. But this time, it is a 190hp B-cy­cle unit found in Audi mod­els since 2017. (Skoda and Audi be­long to the Volk­swa­gen Group.)</p>
    <p>The engine’s de­sign al­lows for higher com­pres­sion ra­tios, with a valve sys­tem which varies air in­take ac­cord­ing to load. It is ef­fi­cient yet torquey.</p>
    <p>In the Su­perb, it sits be­tween the old 2-litre and the pre­vi­ous 1.8-litre in terms of per­for­mance and econ­omy. And like the 1.8-litre, it falls within the Ve­hic­u­lar Emis­sions Scheme’s neu­tral band (the pre­vi­ous 2-litre had a penalty).</p>
    <p>Dur­ing this test-drive, the car av­er­ages 9.2 litres/100kmh, which is not spec­tac­u­lar and quite far from Skoda’s de­clared 6.3 litres.</p>
    <p>But if you con­sider the fol­low­ing two facts, its con­sump­tion fig­ure be­comes more ac­cept­able.</p>
    <p>One, the Su­perb is a big car. It mea­sures 4,869mm tip to tip, 1,864m side to side and has a wheel­base of 2,841mm, mak­ing it closer in size to the Mercedes-Benz</p>
    <p>E-class than the C-class. In­side, it feels roomier than an E-class, with limo-like rear legroom and a 625-litre boot (big­ger than that of an S-class).</p>
    <p>Two, for such a size­able car with a mod­estly-sized engine, its per­for­mance is not too shoddy. The Su­perb has a cen­tury sprint of 7.7 sec­onds and top speed of 238kmh.</p>
    <p>That would make it equiv­a­lent to the per­for­mance of a 2-litre E-class. The Merc, how­ever, has less space and a far loftier price tag.</p>
    <p>Herein lies the long­stand­ing propo­si­tion of Skoda: value for money.</p>
    <p>At $151,900, the Su­perb is $100,000 less ex­pen­sive than the E200. Yes, the Merc has brand ap­peal and is more lux­u­ri­ous, but the Skoda is more ac­com­plished than its price tag sug­gests.</p>
    <p>Be­sides the engine change, the Su­perb is now fit­ted with full LED lights and dy­namic in­di­ca­tors.</p>
    <p>The Lau­rin & Kle­ment vari­ant has a suite of bells and whis­tles. These in­clude 19-inch al­loys, panoramic sun­roof, leather up­hol­stery, pow­ered front seats with mem­ory and ven­ti­la­tion, three-zone cli­mate con­trol, multi-func­tion steer­ing wheel with pad­dle shift, park­ing as­sis­tance, adap­tive sus­pen­sion and adap­tive cruise con­trol.</p>
    <p>An Am­bi­tion vari­ant with fewer fea­tures re­tails for $15,000 less.</p>
    <p>What the lat­est Su­perb lacks, how­ever, is driv­ing en­joy­ment. With a marsh­mal­low ride and de­tached steer­ing, it is as en­gag­ing as a car on a dy­namome­ter. But at least it has more go than the 1.8-litre.</p>
    <p>Pas­sen­gers will no doubt love the Su­perb. Its com­fort-bi­ased chas­sis and ex­tra spa­cious in­te­rior make long jour­neys on less-than-per­fect roads more than bear­able.</p>
    <p>As a com­mute, it of­fers an econ­omy ticket to a first-class ride. Clearly a hard act to fol­low.</p>

